Problem 1: FCN

We studied FCN model with VGG16 network in class. Implement your FCN model using VGG19 network for encoder part of model and test it. I recommend to use colab rather than your laptop.

Now, we've got pre-trained weights and biases. In the following problems, we are going to use the weights and biases from above.

(4) Define your FCN model using the weights and biases in problem (3).

In[8]:
# Your code here
map5 = base_model.layers[-5].output


# sixth convolution layer
conv6 = tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(filters = 4096,
                               kernel_size = (7,7),
                               padding = 'SAME',
                               activation = 'relu', name = 'conv6')(map5)

# 1x1 convolution layers
fcn4 = tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(filters = 4096,
                              kernel_size = (1,1),
                              padding = 'SAME',
                              activation = 'relu', name = 'fcn4')(conv6)

fcn3 = tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(filters = 2,
                              kernel_size = (1,1),
                              padding = 'SAME',
                              activation = 'relu', name = 'fcn3')(fcn4)

# Upsampling layers
fcn2 =  tf.keras.layers.Conv2DTranspose(filters = 512,
                                        kernel_size = (4,4),
                                        strides = (2,2),
                                        padding = 'SAME')(fcn3)

fcn1 =  tf.keras.layers.Conv2DTranspose(filters = 256,
                                        kernel_size = (4,4),
                                        strides = (2,2),
                                        padding = 'SAME')(fcn2 + base_model.layers[-10].output)

output =  tf.keras.layers.Conv2DTranspose(filters = 2,
                                          kernel_size = (16,16),
                                          strides = (4,4),
                                          padding = 'SAME',
                                          activation = 'softmax')(fcn1 + base_model.layers[-15].output)

model = tf.keras.Model(inputs = base_model.inputs, outputs = output)

(9) As you can see, the trained image and image in problem (8) have a different shape. Is it possible to input differently shaped images to the same FCN model without reshaping? If yes, explain why it is possible.

Answer)

Since FCN does not have a fully connected layer, the size of the input image does not matter.
